The rate of spectral changes at 653nm reflects the rate by which TMB is converted. As the Hg2+ concentration is increased, the extent of Hg–Cys complexation increased and more TMB molecules are converted into radicals. It is concluded from Fig. 4
                      that the initial rate of the substrate conversion follows a linear dependence upon the Hg2+ concentration. With the initial Cys concentration set at 5μM, the initial rate increased gradually. In fact, the extent of colored cation radical conversion to colorless TMB was reduced as the Cys concentration was decreased due to its complexation with Hg2+ ion. The enhanced signal intensity is proportional to the mercury ion concentration in the range of 0–0.46μM, with a detection limit of 23nM, which was comparable or even better than the previous reports [48–54], although there are some reports with better detection limits (Table 1
                     ) [42,5,55]. The precision of the method, as expressed by the relative standard deviation (%RSD) obtained from a series of 6 replicate measurements of 0.5μM Hg2+, was found to be 3.1%.
